Quadratic's function derivative¶

  • Quadratic: $f(x) = x^2$
  • Derivative: $f'(x) = 2x$
    • Slope of the tangent line at a given point of $f(x)$.
  • Slope: change on $f(x)$ for each unit of $x$.
    • The higher the slope, the higher the rate of change.
    • Negative slopes mean downward trend.
    • Positive slopes mean upward trend.
    • Slope of 0 means no change. E.g., minimum in quadratic functions.

Gradient Descent¶

  • It is easy to find the minimum if we plot a quadratic function.
  • We can also calculate the minimum using some calculus and algebra.
  • But what if it was computationally intensive to plot or calculate the minimum?
  • Given a point on the function, how can we find the global minimum?
In [48]:
plot_hidden_quadratic(x=28)
plt.show()

Point: (28, -216)
  • A priori we don't know the shape of the parabola.
  • Could be anything.
In [51]:
plot_quad_crossings()

Point: (28, -216)
  • We can compute the slope, that is easy.
  • Now we know we are still a bit far from the minimum.
  • We also know we are on the right side of the parabola.
In [52]:
plot_hidden_quadratic(x=28, show_slope=True); plt.show()

Point: (28, -216)
Slope: 56
  • One option for finding the minimum would be to apply the gradient descent.
  • It consists in iterating and updating the value of $x$.
  • $x_{\text{new}} = x_{\text{old}} - \alpha \cdot \nabla_{x} f(x)$, where
    • $x_{\text{old}}$ is the current $x$ value.
    • $x_{\text{new}}$ is the new $x$ value after the update.
    • $\alpha$ is the learning rate. Defines how fast we update $x$.
    • $\nabla_{x} f(x)$ is the gradient of the function. It is the slope in our example.
In [54]:
plot_hidden_quadratic(x=28, show_slope=True, iters=5,
                      learning_rate=0.1)

  • Take care with the choice of the learning rate!
  • Large values will bounce between the "two slopes" of the quadratic function:
    • It can take more time until convergence.
    • Or it may never converge.
  • Low learning rates will take longer to converge.
    • Although it will finally arrive at some point.
    • Or not if the function has more than 1 minima.

Linear Regression¶

  • Assume we have a single feature $x$.
  • Linear Regression prediction:
    • $\hat{y}_i = w_0 + w_1 \cdot x_i$
  • We said LR optimizes $MSE$.
  • $MSE = \frac{1}{N} \sum{(\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2}$
  • Because $MSE$ is a quadratic function wrt the coefficients $w_n$.
  • $MSE = \frac{1}{N} \sum{( w_0 + w_1 \cdot x_i - y_i)^2}$

  • Liner Regression finds the coefficients $w_i$ that optimize $MSE$:
    • $\hat{y}_i = w_0 + w_1 \cdot x_i$
  • Assume for the sake of the example that we know the optimal $w_0$ is $0$.
  • Can we find the value of $w_1$ that gives the best $MSE$?
  • Yes! For example, by applying gradient descent!
  • We can start with a random $w_1$ and descend until convergence.
In [67]:
w1 = -3894
  • We know $w_0 = 0$.
  • And we have set a random $w_1 = -3894$.
  • We can now calculate all the predictions $\hat{y}_i = w_0 + w_1 \cdot x_i$.
  • Based on the $x_i$ (house square meters) of our dataframe.
  • As we can calculate the predictions $\hat{y}$, we can calculate the $MSE$.
    • $MSE = \frac{1}{N} \sum{(\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2}$
  • We have a bad prediction (magenta) because we selected $w_1$ randomly.
  • Our $MSE$ (red dot) is sky high.
  • We don't know the shape of our quadratic $MSE$,
  • But we can calculate the slope.
  • And apply gradient descent:
    • $w_1 = w_1 - \alpha \cdot \nabla_{w_1} MSE$

Optimize $w_0$ and $w_1$¶

  • Previously, for simplicity, we assumed $w_0 = 0$ and optimized $w_1$.
  • If we want to optimize the whole line equation,
    • $w_0$ and $w_1$,
  • Gradient descent works the same but in 3D, with axis: $w_0$, $w_1$, and $MSE$.
In [562]:
Image('assets/GD_w0_w1.png', width=800)
Out[562]:

Gradient Descent for $w_N$¶

  • Initialize "random" weights $w_N$: one for each feature plus $w_0$.
  • Loop until convergence or max. iterations reached:
    • Perform predictions.
      • $\hat{y} = w_0 + w_1x_1 + w_2x_2 + ... + w_nx_n$ (in the case of LR)
    • Compute loss (e.g., MSE or Logloss).
      • $MSE = \frac{1}{N} \sum{(\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2}$
    • Calculate gradient (i.e., derivative of loss wrt each $w_i$).
    • Update $w_i$:
      • $w_i = w_i - \alpha \cdot \nabla_{w_i} MSE$

Vectorized Form¶

  • Computationally more efficient.
  • It's the same as above but using linear algebra.
  • Given a matrix of features $X$.
  • Initialize "random" vector of weights $\mathbf{w}$.
  • Loop until convergence or max. iterations reached:
    • Compute vector of predictions $\hat{\mathbf{y}}$.
      • $\hat{\mathbf{y}} = w_0 + X \mathbf{w}$ (in the case of LR)
    • Compute loss (e.g., MSE or Logloss).
      • $MSE = \frac{1}{N} \sum{(\hat{y}_i - y_i)^2}$
    • Calculate gradient $\nabla_{\mathbf{w}} MSE$.
    • Update $\mathbf{w}$:
      • $\mathbf{w} = \mathbf{w} - \alpha \cdot \nabla_{\mathbf{w}} MSE$

Types of GD¶

In [2]:
Image('assets/types_gd.png', width=800)
Out[2]:

Batch GD¶

  • Until convergence or max. iterations:
    • Calculate error for each sample in the train set.
    • Update weights after evaluating all training samples.
  • Pros:
    • Stable convergence.
    • Consistent gradient.
  • Cons:
    • Computationally intensive.
    • Prone to getting stuck in local minima.

Stochastic GD¶

  • Until convergence or max. iterations:
    • For each sample in the train set:
      • Calculate error for a single sample.
      • Update weights based on this sample.
  • Pros:
    • Fast updates.
    • Potential local minima scape.
  • Cons:
    • Noisy convergence.
    • Inconsistent gradient.

Mini-batch GD¶

  • Split train set into small batch sizes (mini-batches).
  • Until convergence or max. iterations:
    • Apply batch GD on each mini-batch.
  • Mixed Pros and Cons of batch and stochastic GD.
